response:
We can factor the numerator and denominator as follows: \[\frac{|(x - 9)(x + 9)|}{x(x - 36)} < 0.\]The expression is less than zero when the numerator and denominator have opposite signs.  The numerator is zero when $x = \pm 9,$ and the denominator is zero when $x = 0$ or $x = 36.$  We can use a sign chart to determine the sign of the expression in each of the intervals $(-\infty, -9),$ $(-9, 0),$ $(0, 9),$ $(9, 36),$ and $(36, \infty).$

[asy]
unitsize(0.5 cm);

real f(real x) {
  return(abs((x - 9)*(x + 9))/(x*(x - 36)));
}

draw((-12,0)--(40,0));
draw((0,-12)--(0,12));
draw((-12,-12)--(0,12),dashed);
draw((-12,12)--(0,-12),dashed);
draw((-9,-12)--(-9,12),dashed);
draw((0,-12)--(0,12),dashed);
draw((9,-12)--(9,12),dashed);
draw((36,-12)--(36,12),dashed);
label("$-\infty$", (-12,0), S);
label("$-9$", (-9,0), S);
label("$0$", (0,0), S);
label("$9$", (9,0), S);
label("$36$", (36,0), S);
label("$\infty$", (40,0), S);
label("$f(x)$", (0,-12), L, red);
[/asy]

We see that the expression is negative when $x \in (-9, 0) \cup (9, 36).$  Therefore, the solution is \[x \in \boxed{(-9,0) \cup (9,36)}.\]

